{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2ffbe692-a089-4977-84dc-fdc11284b268","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard .NET MAUI property — that's likely why it has no effect. You need **platform-specific** settings:\n\n### iOS\nAdd the iOS-specific namespace and disable safe area on the page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"\n             Padding=\"0\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n### Android\nAndroid doesn't go edge-to-edge by default (until API 35). In your `MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n\n    if (Window != null)\n    {\n        AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n        Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Key points\n- **`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"`** — lets content extend behind the notch/home indicator on iOS\n- **`SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)`** — lets content draw behind system bars on Android\n- Set **`Padding=\"0\"`** on the page and **`Margin=\"0\"`** on the Image explicitly\n- Use **`Aspect=\"AspectFill\"`** so the image fills the available space","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ca8c1e35-b95d-4ce6-a55e-bef99e6f8e0e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `IgnoreSafeArea` on the view itself - This is important. Setting `SafeAreaEdges` on the page controls which edges respect safe areas, but individual views may still respect safe areas by default.\n\n\n2. On Android, edge-to-edge is automatic for apps targeting API 35+, but earlier versions need explicit configuration. On iOS, you'll need to set `IgnoreSafeArea` on the specific views to override the default safe area insets.\n\n3. In .NET MAUI, the approach differs by platform: on iOS, you use the platform-specific namespace to set `UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on the page, while Android requires configuring the window to draw behind system bars. I'm setting up the Android window configuration to draw behind the system bars using `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows`, and considering that .NET 9+ may have newer APIs for edge-to-edge support that could simplify this. The user's `SafeAreaEdges` property isn't standard MAUI, so they likely need the proper iOS safe area handling and Android edge-to-edge setup instead.","outputTokens":1454,"requestId":"7FD0:2AEA3B:42FE669:498A61C:69F15960"},"id":"6e1fd8f1-8edb-4c91-a1e9-072ee627fecd","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:06:03.119Z","parentId":"fe1e38a5-c633-4d0c-b62d-1fa85bad214a"}
